04952nam a22006495i 9780822381136DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20012001ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223811367 a10.1515/97808223811362doi  a(DE-B1597)553424  a(OCoLC)1229160747  a(OCoLC)1167366003  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aKF4755b.P67 2001 7aLAW0940002bisacsh1 aPost, Robert C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPrejudicial Appearances :bThe Logic of American Antidiscrimination Law /cRobert C. Post, K. Anthony Appiah, Reva B. Siegel, Thomas C. Grey, Judith Butler. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2001] 4cÂ©2001  a1 online resource (178 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPrejudicial Appearances: The Logic of American Antidiscrimination Law -- tStereotypes and the Shaping of Identity -- t''Appearances Aside'' -- tCover Blindness -- tDiscrimination in the Eyes of the Law: How ''Color Blindness'' Discourse Disrupts and Rationalizes Social Stratification -- tResponse to Commentators -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Prejudicial Appearances noted legal scholar Robert C. Post argues modern American antidiscrimination law should not be conceived as protecting the transcendental dignity of individual persons but instead as transforming social practices that define and sustain potentially oppressive categories like race or gender. Arguing that the prevailing logic of American antidiscrimination law is misleading, Post lobbies for deploying sociological understandings to reevaluate the antidiscrimination project in ways that would render the law more effective and just.Four distinguished commentators respond to Post's provocative essay. Each adopts a distinctive perspective. K. Anthony Appiah investigates the philosophical logic of stereotyping and of equality. Questioning whether the law ought to endorse any social practices that define persons, Judith Butler explores the tension between sociological and postmodern approaches to antidiscrimination law. Thomas C. Grey examines whether Post's proposal can be reconciled with the values of the rule of law. And Reva B. Siegel applies critical race theory to query whether antidiscrimination law's reshaping of race and gender should best be understood in terms of practices of subordination and stratification.By illuminating the consequential rhetorical maneuvers at the heart of contemporary U.S. antidiscrimination law, Prejudical Appearances forces readers to reappraise the relationship between courts of law and social behavior. As such, it will enrich scholars interested in the relationships between law, rhetoric, postmodernism, race, and gender.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aDiscriminationxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aPhysical-appearance-based bias. 0aPrejudices. 7aLAW / Discrimination.2bisacsh1 aAppiah, K. Anthony, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aButler, Judith, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aButler, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAppiah, K. Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSiegel, Reva B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPost, Robert C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSiegel, Reva B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aGrey, Thomas C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.151